{
  "doc_id": "14260",
  "text": "Cluster 5 contains 12 different genes, which are preferentially induced in DP thymocytes, with expression levels at least 2-fold higher in DP than in SP thymocytes. This group contains both signaling molecules and transcription regulators. Signaling molecules include suppressor of cytokine signaling-1 (socs-1), TNFR-associated factor 3 (traf3), SH3 domain binding protein 2 (3bp2), prostaglandin E2 receptor EP4 (ptger4) and the small GTPase rad. The Rad protein belongs to the RGK (Rad/Gem/Kir) subfamily within the Ras superfamily and has been shown to antagonize Rho signaling by binding to the downstream effector Rho kinase (ROK/ROCK) [CITATION_1] . Thus, in addition to the GTPases Rho and Rac-1 that are implicated in survival and selection of thymocytes [CITATION_2] , rad appears to be similarly involved. TRAF proteins mediate signal transduction of the TNFR superfamily. TRAF3 in particular binds to CD40 and LTbR, and has been implicated in LTbmediated cell death [CITATION_3] . Interestingly, LTb is induced upon VSV8 injection (see Fig. 3 ) suggesting an LTb±TRAF3-mediated apoptotic pathway in thymic selection. Transcriptional regulators in cluster 5 are the NFkB inhibitor ikba, egr1, the Egr1-inhibitor nab2 and DNA methyltransferase 3A (dnmt3a), which mediates transcriptional silencing by methylation of DNA [CITATION_4] . The majority of cluster 5 genes are induced rapidly after VSV8 injection, implying regulation at the level of early signaling initiated by the TCR.",
